<p>I don&#8217;t get it. You pay at the restaurant simply out of a desire to keep your promise (or, if you wish, a desire to avoid the discomfort that would ensue if you didn&#8217;t do what was &#8220;normal&#8221; and committed to). How is this a &#8220;desire-independent reason for action&#8221;? Do you have other examples?</p>

